03516nam a22004695i 9780773588707DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735887077 a10.1515/97807735887072doi  a(DE-B1597)655785  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPS8101.G37 ǂb B69 2013eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a813.00992871 aBoyd, Shelley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGarden Plots :bCanadian Women Writers and Their Literary Gardens /cShelley Boyd. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b18 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tGarden Plots -- t“[T]ransplanted into our gardens”: Susanna Moodie, Catharine Parr Traill, and the Backwoods Kitchen Garden -- tWhen Authors are Gardeners: Susanna Moodie’s and Catharine Parr Traill’s Figurative “Plots” -- t“Then a living house”: Gabrielle Roy’s Domestication of the Bower -- t“A Saucer of Green”: Carol Shields and Domestic Paradise -- tTurning the Earth: Lorna Crozier the Gardener-Poet -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCanadian literature has long been preoccupied with the wilderness and the landscape, but the garden has remained neglected terrain. In Garden Plots, Shelley Boyd focuses on private, domestic gardens tended by individual gardeners, to show how modest, everyday spaces provide fertile grounds for the imagination. Combining the history of gardening with literary analysis, Garden Plots explores the use of the garden motif in the works of five authors: Susanna Moodie, Catharine Parr Traill, Gabrielle Roy, Carol Shields, and Lorna Crozier. With works spanning the nineteenth to twenty-first centuries, these writers reveal the associations between the arts of writing and gardening, the evolving role of the female gardener, and the changes that take place in Canada's literary gardens over time. With the task of understanding our connection to the physical environment becoming increasingly important, Garden Plots explores the subtle relations between place and narrative. This fresh, literary approach to Canada's gardening culture reveals that gardens grow and change not simply in the earth, but also in the pages of our texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCanadian literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aGardens in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358870740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588707423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588707/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles